05127nam a22007935i 9780226638126DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019719887  a97802266381267 a10.7208/97802266381262doi  a(DE-B1597)535783  a(OCoLC)1120698358  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aRB155.5 4aRB155.5 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a616.0422231 aNavon, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobilizing Mutations :bHuman Genetics in the Age of Patient Advocacy /cDaniel Navon. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b11 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: From Mutations to New Kinds of People -- t1. Genomic Designation: How Genetics Creates New Medical Conditions -- t2. Immobile Mutations: Nowhere to Go in the 1960s and 1970s (and the Exception That Proves the Rule) -- t3. Leveraging Mutations: Going from the Rare to the Common in Human Genetics -- t4. The Loops That Tie: Mutations in the Trading Zone of Autism Genetics -- t5. Assembling a New Kind of Person -- t6. Mutations in the Clinic: Reframing Illness and Redirecting Medical Practice -- t7. Remaking the Normal versus the Pathological in Genetic Medicine -- t8. The Future for Genomic Designation and the New Prenatal Testing Landscape -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith every passing year, more and more people learn that they or their young or unborn children carries a genetic mutation. But what does this mean for the way we understand a person? Today, genetic mutations are being used to diagnose novel conditions like the XYY, Fragile X, NGLY1 mutation, and 22q11.2 Deletion syndromes, carving out rich new categories of human disease and difference. Daniel Navon calls this form of categorization “genomic designation,” and in Mobilizing Mutations he shows how mutations, and the social factors that surround them, are reshaping human classification. Drawing on a wealth of fieldwork and historical material, Navon presents a sociological account of the ways genetic mutations have been mobilized and transformed in the sixty years since it became possible to see abnormal human genomes, providing a new vista onto the myriad ways contemporary genetic testing can transform people’s lives. Taking us inside these shifting worlds of research and advocacy over the last half century, Navon reveals the ways in which knowledge about genetic mutations can redefine what it means to be ill, different, and ultimately, human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHuman chromosome abnormalities. 0aHuman genetics. 0aMedical genetics. 0aMutation (Biology) 0aMutation (Biology). 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aautism.  abiosociality.  aclassification.  ageneticization.  agenetics.  agenomic designation.  aidentity.  alooping.  amutations.  apatient activism.  apatient advocacy.  areiterated fact-making.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019 Englishz978311061053608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019z9783110606386oZDB-23-DPM08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226638126423Coveruhttps://w